        John Hawkins

        4th December 2022

        Yes I agree there needs to be a rethink. I think the problem partly stems from OCC trying to do two contradictory things at once and ending up not doing either well. Firstly, they want a chart that reflects the contemporary way of listening/buying music i.e. with a big role for streaming. Secondly, they want a chart they can use for making comparisons between recent acts and those from earlier decades when music was consumed by buying vinyl or CDs.

        The switch from buying vinyl singles to paid downloads or vinyl LPs to CDs was not so much a problem as it kept the idea of purchases. But streams are more plays than purchases. People who bought a vinyl single would play it over following months but it only affected the charts in the week it was first bought. So its not surprising that songs stay in the charts longer when the charts are based on plays. Arbitrary rules about altering calculations depending on whether a single is called a re-entry or has dropped by a certain amount are a very poor way of adjusting for this.

        I think there should be two charts. The first a chart of purchases that would be the successor to the charts that started in the 1950s. The second should be a chart of plays only going back to when streaming started to dominate.

        I agree a single should count as re-entry regardless of whether the company promotes it as a reissue, whether it is on a different label and whether it has a different number. ('3 lions' is a tricky case where the same artists partly rerecord a song with some changes to the lyrics).
